==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Locofoco
<hw>Lo`co*fo"co</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of uncertain
etymol.; perh. for L. <ets>loco foci</ets> instead of fire; or,
according to Bartlett, it was called so from a self-lighting cigar, with
a match composition at the end, invented in 1834 by <person>John
Marck</person> of New York, and called by him <ets>locofoco cigar</ets>,
in imitation of the word <ets>locomotive</ets>, which by the uneducated
was supposed to mean, self-moving.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A friction
match.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A nickname formerly given to a member of the
Democratic party.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The name was first applied, in 1834, to a portion of the
Democratic party, because, at a meeting in Tammany Hall, New York, in
which there was great diversity of sentiment, the chairman left his
seat, and the lights were extinguished, for the purpose of dissolving
the meeting; when those who were opposed to an adjournment produced
<xex>locofoco</xex> matches, rekindled the lights, continued the
meeting, and accomplished their object.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>locoism</ent>⟦br⟧
